		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27516597">Uchouten Kazoku<br />
<br />
Uchouten Kazoku manages to effortlessly weave traditional and modern cultures into a story that creates powerful drama, interesting politics, and endearing characters. Its only real flaw story-wise is that it doesn't even really begin until abour three or four episodes in, but even that can be forgiven since the characters are set up so that they can drive the story without becoming more important than it.<br />
<br />
Honorable mentions:<br />
Maoyuu Maou Yuusha<br />
- Interesting setting and world building but has better ideas and individual scenes than a full blown story<br />
Zetsuen no Tempest<br />
- Well-constructed story with interesting mechanics but a pretty unexciting ending and (mostly) unengaging characters</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by NavyCherub, 01-22-14, 10:45 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
That one may smile, and smile, and be a villain.&quot;</div></td>
